properties.Title: Winter Storm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Winter storm threatening Saturday night into Sunday. After a period of snow giving a few cm of snow tonight into Saturday, a strong moisture laden low from Texas and Louisiana will bring a large area of heavier snow to Northeastern Ontario Saturday night into Sunday. Total snowfall amounts of 15 to 25 cm are possible in many areas. In addition, strong northeast winds gusting to 60 km/h will whip up freshly fallen snow with frequent very low to nil visibility in blowing snow especially in exposed areas. Travel will likely be significantly affected. Travel plans should be changed accordingly. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become icy and slippery. Winter storm watches are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

A moisture laden low from Texas may bring an ice storm to parts of Southern Ontario Saturday afternoon and Saturday night. Rain will turn over to freezing rain on Saturday. The changeover will firsty occur in the morning over the Bruce Peninsula then over remaining areas by noon. An extended period of freezing rain, mixed at times with ice pellets, appears likely before precipitation comes to an end on Sunday morning. An extended period of freezing rain is expected, along with ice accretion of 10 to 20 mm in many areas. Ice accretion may reach 25 mm in a few locales by Sunday morning. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots will become icy, slippery and extremely hazardous. properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A soaker on tap Saturday. Freezing rain possible Saturday night. Very strong southwest winds Sunday. Occasional light rain or drizzle is expected to continue tonight. However, rain will be more continuous and heavy at times Saturday into Sunday morning. Total rainfall amounts of 40 to 60 mm are possible with most of the rain falling Saturday into Saturday night. For areas further away from Lake Ontario, rain may change to freezing rain by Saturday evening and may last for several hours. Strong southwest winds are also expected Sunday morning, especially along the Lake Ontario shoreline where winds may gust up to 80 km/h. There remains considerable uncertainty with the location of freezing rain. Freezing rain and wind warnings may be issued as necessary. Travel will be impacted throughout Southern Ontario Saturday into Sunday. For information concerning flooding, please consult your local conservation authority or Ontario Ministry of Natural Resources and Forestry district office. ### Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rainfall, combined with melting snow, is expected. The frozen ground has a reduced ability to absorb this rainfall. A soaker on tap. A moisture laden low from Texas will bring a significant heavy rainfall event to Southern Ontario Saturday. Rain is expected to become continuous and heavy at times overnight then continue Saturday. Total rainfall amounts of 40 to 60 mm are anticipated by Saturday evening. Since the ground is frozen, the winter rainfall warning criterion of 25 mm in 24 hours is being met. The rain may change over to freezing rain beginning Saturday evening as temperatures dip to near the zero degree mark. Freezing rain warnings may be needed as this event draws closer. Strong westerly winds gusting to 60 km/h Sunday morning coupled with possible ice build-up on tree branches and power lines may result in local power outages. For information concerning flooding, please consult your local conservation authority or Ontario Ministry of Natural Resources and Forestry district office. ### Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Rainfall warnings are issued when significant rainfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.
